{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637523"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17664"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17664"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.18,0.09,0.27,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78235"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10378"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8485"},{"type":"tags","id":"9923"},{"type":"tags","id":"10007"},{"type":"tags","id":"10539"},{"type":"tags","id":"10541"},{"type":"tags","id":"10545"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24300"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78235"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe kidneys play a crucial role in acid-base homeostasis through the reabsorption of filtered bicarbonate in the proximal tubule.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first step required to facilitate bicarbonate reabsorption in the proximal tubule?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generation of new bicarbonate molecules","Transport of bicarbonate directly across tubular cells","Conversion of carbon dioxide to bicarbonate","Secretion of hydrogen ions into the tubular lumen","Formation of carbonic acid from hydrogen ions and bicarbonate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first step required to facilitate bicarbonate reabsorption is \u003Cstrong\u003Esecretion of hydrogen ions into the tubular lumen\u003C/strong\u003E via sodium-hydrogen exchangers. These hydrogen ions then combine with filtered bicarbonate to form carbonic acid (H2CO3). The subsequent steps involve carbonic anhydrase-mediated conversion of carbonic acid to carbon dioxide and water, diffusion of carbon dioxide into tubular cells, and carbonic anhydrase-mediated regeneration of bicarbonate within the cells, which can then be reabsorbed. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of carbonic acid from hydrogen ions and bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as the second step in the process, after hydrogen ions have been secreted into the lumen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of carbon dioxide to bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E takes place later in the process within the tubular cells, not as an initial step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of bicarbonate directly across tubular cells\u003C/strong\u003E is not possible as bicarbonate must first be converted to carbon dioxide to cross cell membranes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneration of new bicarbonate molecules\u003C/strong\u003E represents a separate process from bicarbonate reabsorption and occurs through different mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The carbonic acid-bicarbonate buffer system is the most important buffer in blood, maintaining pH between 7.35-7.45.","Carbonic anhydrase in the proximal tubule catalyses the interconversion between H2O and CO2 and carbonic acid (and its dissociative ions)."],"references":["Shaw I, Gregory K. Acid-base balance: a review of normal physiology. BJA Educ. 2022 Oct;22(10):396-401. doi: 10.1016/j.bjae.2022.06.003. Epub 2022 Aug 18. Erratum in: BJA Educ. 2023 Jan;23(1):39. doi: 10.1016/j.bjae.2022.11.004. PMID: 36132879; PMCID: PMC9482868."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17664"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63644"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T22:25:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T22:26:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10378"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78235"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","p